01:08:20.370 --> 01:08:23.630
In other words, when you take
what comes out of here, you

01:08:23.630 --> 01:08:30.270
multiply it, and you shift it
down in frequency by s sub c,

01:08:30.270 --> 01:08:34.615
what happens is that this gets
shifted down in frequency by s

01:08:34.615 --> 01:08:39.770
sub c and this channel filter
gets shifted down in frequency

01:08:39.770 --> 01:08:43.620
by f of c and therefore, what
happens is the effect of

01:08:43.620 --> 01:08:48.320
passing y of t through
a base band filter --

01:08:48.320 --> 01:08:54.586
h-hat of f plus fc and t or
0 for f, less than or

01:08:54.586 --> 01:08:56.420
equal to minus fc.

01:08:56.420 --> 01:09:01.030
So far, this is all kind of
straightforward and not too

01:09:01.030 --> 01:09:02.280
mysterious.

01:09:09.810 --> 01:09:13.290
So you wind up then in --

01:09:13.290 --> 01:09:17.010
and this is pure analogy to
what we did before --

01:09:17.010 --> 01:09:23.210
the output is then going to be
the integral of this Fourier

01:09:23.210 --> 01:09:26.560
transform of the input.

01:09:26.560 --> 01:09:31.433
The system function for the
baseband filter times e to the

01:09:31.433 --> 01:09:33.530
2 pi ift df.

01:09:33.530 --> 01:09:37.280
Same equation as we had before,
but before we did it

01:09:37.280 --> 01:09:43.350
at pass band and now we're
doing it at baseband .

01:09:43.350 --> 01:09:49.290
For the ray tracing model that
we looked at, this function

01:09:49.290 --> 01:09:55.420
here down at baseband is going
to be the same as it was at

01:09:55.420 --> 01:10:01.280
pass band, except in place of
the 2 pi i tau jft, we now

01:10:01.280 --> 01:10:07.840
have f plus the carrier
frequency times tau jft.

01:10:07.840 --> 01:10:12.020
So when we take the inverse
Fourier transform of this,

01:10:12.020 --> 01:10:14.240
we're given parameter t.

01:10:14.240 --> 01:10:18.320
What we're going to wind up with
is this quantity here.

01:10:18.320 --> 01:10:22.380
This is the same as we had
before, with the difference

01:10:22.380 --> 01:10:26.820
that now we're stuck with this
carrier frequency times

01:10:26.820 --> 01:10:31.450
propogation delay, which
is occurring in time t.

01:10:31.450 --> 01:10:36.520
We still have the same delta
functions here and the output

01:10:36.520 --> 01:10:39.210
v of t is the same time variant

01:10:39.210 --> 01:10:43.570
convolution as we had before.

01:10:43.570 --> 01:10:46.680
I'm doing this much too
fast for you to follow

01:10:46.680 --> 01:10:48.530
this in real time.

01:10:48.530 --> 01:10:51.160
What I'm saying is, this is
exactly the same thing as we

01:10:51.160 --> 01:10:56.630
did before and the only thing
new that happens is now this

01:10:56.630 --> 01:11:02.110
carrier frequency term is coming
in here on this term.

01:11:02.110 --> 01:11:06.330
If we're using the ray tracing
model then, v of t is equal to

01:11:06.330 --> 01:11:08.860
this quantity here.

01:11:08.860 --> 01:11:13.530
The reason I write this down is
that this shows you quite

01:11:13.530 --> 01:11:18.970
simply what's going on in terms
of the Doppler shift,

01:11:18.970 --> 01:11:23.480
because these terms here, these
delay terms are changing

01:11:23.480 --> 01:11:27.470
with Doppler shift and now we're
going to see exactly

01:11:27.470 --> 01:11:28.720
what they do to us.

01:11:36.010 --> 01:11:38.250
So we're going to represent
the propogation

01:11:38.250 --> 01:11:40.070
delay on each path.

01:11:40.070 --> 01:11:43.840
That's tau j of t, which is
tau j prime, which is the

01:11:43.840 --> 01:11:49.960
propogation delay of time zero
minus the Doppler shift times

01:11:49.960 --> 01:11:52.460
t divided by f.

01:11:52.460 --> 01:11:56.720
This is just Doppler shift,
which is a frequency term, and

01:11:56.720 --> 01:11:59.770
it's increasing linearly.

01:11:59.770 --> 01:12:04.030
The propogation delay is
increasing linearly with t.

01:12:04.030 --> 01:12:14.960
The Doppler shift is a shift in
frequency and, as I think

01:12:14.960 --> 01:12:19.030
we saw before, you need a 1 over
f to compensate for this

01:12:19.030 --> 01:12:19.770
Doppler shift.

01:12:19.770 --> 01:12:23.010
Namely, this is in
terms of hertz.

01:12:23.010 --> 01:12:24.710
This is in terms of hertz.

01:12:24.710 --> 01:12:26.300
This is in terms of time.

01:12:26.300 --> 01:12:28.280
This is in terms of time.

01:12:28.280 --> 01:12:31.020
So you need this frequency here
to be dimensionally right

01:12:31.020 --> 01:12:32.790
at any rate.

01:12:32.790 --> 01:12:36.580
If we're using narrow band
communication, then v of t is

01:12:36.580 --> 01:12:40.290
just going to be this difference
here, which is just

01:12:40.290 --> 01:12:46.180
the last equation with the
Doppler shift put into it.

01:12:46.180 --> 01:12:52.600
So all of this says that when
we're now looking at things at

01:12:52.600 --> 01:12:57.060
base band instead of a pass
band, what has happened is

01:12:57.060 --> 01:13:00.750
that this term has been added.

01:13:00.750 --> 01:13:05.280
Before, we just had these delay
terms here and we had

01:13:05.280 --> 01:13:07.330
these attenuation terms.

01:13:07.330 --> 01:13:12.090
Now what's happening is because
we are modulating up

01:13:12.090 --> 01:13:16.885
with carrier frequency s sub c,
we then get a Doppler shift

01:13:16.885 --> 01:13:19.140
that moves us down
a little bit.

01:13:19.140 --> 01:13:21.730
We're then moving
down by s sub c.

01:13:21.730 --> 01:13:25.090
What we wind up with is
something which is off by that

01:13:25.090 --> 01:13:27.290
Doppler shift.

01:13:27.290 --> 01:13:30.180
If we only had a single
term, we wouldn't be

01:13:30.180 --> 01:13:31.940
demodulating by s sub c.

01:13:31.940 --> 01:13:35.180
We'd be demodulating by
something which would get rid

01:13:35.180 --> 01:13:36.780
of this term for us.

01:13:36.780 --> 01:13:39.840
Then all we'd have is just
some arbitrary phase term

01:13:39.840 --> 01:13:41.300
here, because this
isn't important.

01:13:41.300 --> 01:13:43.350
This is just a phase term.

01:13:43.350 --> 01:13:46.960
This is the term which
is important.

01:13:46.960 --> 01:13:49.276
The reason for going through
all of this --

01:13:49.276 --> 01:13:52.780
and I'm going to come back
to this next time --

01:13:52.780 --> 01:13:57.510
is that when you use frequency
recovery at the receiver and

01:13:57.510 --> 01:14:02.420
you always use frequency
recovery at the receiver,

01:14:02.420 --> 01:14:05.270
what's going to happen is you're
not going to shift

01:14:05.270 --> 01:14:07.500
down by s of c.

01:14:07.500 --> 01:14:13.000
You're going to shift down s of
c, plus some average value

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:14.940
of Doppler shift.

01:14:14.940 --> 01:14:18.020
If they have a bunch of terms,
each with different Doppler

01:14:18.020 --> 01:14:23.330
shifts in them, when you try to
measure how much Doppler --

01:14:23.330 --> 01:14:26.540
when you try to measure what
the received carrier is,

01:14:26.540 --> 01:14:28.950
you're going to be frustrated
by all of these different

01:14:28.950 --> 01:14:29.910
Doppler shifts.

01:14:29.910 --> 01:14:32.760
You're going to come up with
some average value in your

01:14:32.760 --> 01:14:36.510
frequency circuit, which means
that in place of this

01:14:36.510 --> 01:14:40.890
quantity, you will get something
which replaces each

01:14:40.890 --> 01:14:45.820
of these D sub j's by not the
actual Doppler shift, but by

01:14:45.820 --> 01:14:48.300
how far this Doppler shift
is away from the

01:14:48.300 --> 01:14:50.680
main Doppler shift.

01:14:50.680 --> 01:14:55.010
So these terms here, which are
the things that make this

01:14:55.010 --> 01:15:00.090
system function in here change
with time, are in fact

01:15:00.090 --> 01:15:04.390
changing according to how far
away each of these Doppler

01:15:04.390 --> 01:15:07.770
shifts are from the main Doppler
shift, which means

01:15:07.770 --> 01:15:11.400
that the amount of time this
system function in here is

01:15:11.400 --> 01:15:18.770
going to remain stable depends
on how much the Doppler shifts

01:15:18.770 --> 01:15:22.060
vary from each other on
these different paths.

01:15:22.060 --> 01:15:24.840
In other words, the important
thing is the Doppler spread

01:15:24.840 --> 01:15:27.580
between the biggest Doppler
shifts and the smallest

01:15:27.580 --> 01:15:29.200
Doppler shifts.

01:15:29.200 --> 01:15:32.930
That Doppler spread is going to
determine how long you've

01:15:32.930 --> 01:15:36.700
got something that looks like a
linear time invariant system

01:15:36.700 --> 01:15:40.530
function which says that every
once in awhile, if you're

01:15:40.530 --> 01:15:44.390
trying to measure what's going
on at the channel, at

01:15:44.390 --> 01:15:47.050
intervals of time approximately
one over two

01:15:47.050 --> 01:15:49.760
times the Doppler spread, you're
going to have to change

01:15:49.760 --> 01:15:52.050
those measurements.

01:15:52.050 --> 01:15:55.900
So whether you can make cellular
telephony work or not

01:15:55.900 --> 01:16:00.150
depends on whether you can make
measurements at a speed

01:16:00.150 --> 01:16:04.830
which is equal to one over two
times the Doppler spread.

01:16:04.830 --> 01:16:07.930
I'm going to do more about
that next time.

01:16:07.930 --> 01:16:10.890
I don't expect you to
understand it now.

01:16:10.890 --> 01:16:15.350
Maybe after you read about it
and we talk about it more,

01:16:15.350 --> 01:16:16.600
because in fact that's --

01:16:20.760 --> 01:16:24.980
if you look at this question of
Doppler spread and what its

01:16:24.980 --> 01:16:28.910
effect is on how long a system
looks like it's time

01:16:28.910 --> 01:16:32.630
invariant, this is one of
the key parameters to

01:16:32.630 --> 01:16:36.110
understanding how any
kind of wireless

01:16:36.110 --> 01:16:37.360
system is going to work.

